NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As to the play, Dee needs to ruff a few diamonds in dummy before pulling trumps. It is the same mistake Patti made on an earlier hand when she pulled trumps instead of ruffing clubs. Wen dummy is short of a suit, you often need to ruff in dummy before pulling all the trumps. That is a very common reason to delay pulling trumps. This hand is one good illustration, as was the earlier hand.|
PG| ***** 127 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, let's talk about the Splinter some more, and what kind of cards Dee should have to get her interested in slam. When partner splinters, the best holding you can have is 3 or 4 small. If, for example, Patti had splintered in spades, Dee's hand suddenly becomes very good  because there are no wasted values in spades, which makes it more likely that Dee's honors fit better with Patti's.|
PG| ***** 128 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Conversely, the worst thing you can have in a splinter suit is honors, other than the Ace. Dee's holding in diamonds is particularly bad, given the diamond splinter which demonstrates why it was difficult to even make 4H much less 6H. So, when partner splinters, you should like 3 or 4 small, or 3 or 4 to the Ace in the splintered suit and you should discount any other honors you have in the splinter suit.|
